				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		<li class="comment even depth-2 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-7376">
		<div id="comment-7376">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='https://0.gravatar.com/avatar/374198903dbd5d6a8949c27f35aec42c?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='https://historyofnavymedicine.org' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>SemiSaltyDoc</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="https://jamesthomassnyder.com/2019/09/24/the-price-of-promotion/#comment-7376">
				September 25, 2019 at 10:54</a>			</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

			<div class="comment-body"><p>I sat on two Navy Selection boards. The one tool in the Navy Fitness Reports (our EER equivalent) that I found consistently useful was the peer ranking box, where the officer’s performance was ranked with his peers within the command. We tended to discount or ignore the narratives unless they were written by a senior officer known to the board to be a tough but fair and objective judge of performance.</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
				<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://jamesthomassnyder.com/2019/09/24/the-price-of-promotion/?replytocom=7376#respond' data-commentid="7376" data-postid="1444" data-belowelement="comment-7376" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to SemiSaltyDoc" aria-label='Reply to SemiSaltyDoc'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
